<body>
    <h1>Churn Prediction Project</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h2 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-Step1:PerformsimpleEDAtoUnderstand=
theDataset"><strong>Step 1: Perform simple EDA to Understand the Dataset</s=
trong></h2>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-ProblemDefinition:">Problem Definition:</h=
3>
<p>The objective is to&nbsp;<strong>predict </strong>whether users will mak=
e a <strong>fifth </strong>purchase based on their <strong>four most recent=
 purchases</strong>. In addition, the purchase <strong>probability </strong=
>should be estimated for each user.</p>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-Data:">Data:</h3>
<p>order_history:<br>
  It contains 800 rows. Each of the 200 users has exactly 4 recorded transa=
ctions.</p>
<p>labels:<br>
  Labels are available for 120 users (105 loyal and 15 churned). The remain=
ing 80 users do not have labels, and their outcomes need to be predicted.</=
p>
<p>Features:<br>
  The values for <em>order_value</em> and <em>carton_count</em> have alread=
y been scaled. They are normalized and range between 0 and 1.</p>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-IdentifiedChallenges:">Identified Challeng=
es:</h3>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Imbalanced Data:</strong> Since the number of loyal users (Cla=
ss 1) is significantly higher than the number of churned users (Class 0), a=
 model that always predicts Class 1 would achieve<strong> high accuracy</st=
rong> but would not be practically useful. Therefore, evaluation metrics su=
ch as <strong>F1-Score</strong> or <strong>AUC-ROC</strong> should be used =
instead of relying solely on accuracy.</p></li>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Limited Data Volume:</strong> With only 120 labeled records av=
ailable for training, the dataset is not sufficient for complex models, and=
 there is a risk of overfitting.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manu=
al-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image" draggable=3D"false" width=
=3D"350" src=3D"b63d83edd318f97888c191881a628245" data-image-src=3D"/downlo=
ad/attachments/524654655/Screenshot%202026-02-23%20173306.png?version=3D1&a=
mp;modificationDate=3D1771855401344&amp;api=3Dv2" data-unresolved-comment-c=
ount=3D"0" data-linked-resource-id=3D"524654712" data-linked-resource-versi=
on=3D"1" data-linked-resource-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resource-defa=
ult-alias=3D"Screenshot 2026-02-23 173306.png" data-base-url=3D"https://con=
fluence.snapp.ir" data-linked-resource-content-type=3D"image/png" data-link=
ed-resource-container-id=3D"524654655" data-linked-resource-container-versi=
on=3D"17" alt=3D"" height=3D"251"></span></p>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-RFM:">RFM:</h3>
<p>In retail businesses, the&nbsp;<strong>RFM (Recency, Frequency, Monetary=
)</strong> framework is essential. Since <em>Frequency</em> is constant for=
 all users (<strong>4 purchases each</strong>), the analysis should focus o=
n <strong>Recency</strong> (time gap between purchases) and <strong>Monetar=
y</strong> (purchase value).</p>
<p>High Correlation:<br>
  There is a strong correlation (0.89) between <em>order_value</em> and <em=
>carton_count</em>. This indicates that users who purchase <strong>more car=
tons </strong>naturally tend to have <strong>higher invoice values</strong>=
.</p>
<p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manu=
al-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image" draggable=3D"false" width=
=3D"350" src=3D"eaccc6ab0c17280d7db2db622bb54998" data-image-src=3D"/downlo=
ad/attachments/524654655/Screenshot%202026-02-23%20191355.png?version=3D1&a=
mp;modificationDate=3D1771861512789&amp;api=3Dv2" data-unresolved-comment-c=
ount=3D"0" data-linked-resource-id=3D"524654803" data-linked-resource-versi=
on=3D"1" data-linked-resource-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resource-defa=
ult-alias=3D"Screenshot 2026-02-23 191355.png" data-base-url=3D"https://con=
fluence.snapp.ir" data-linked-resource-content-type=3D"image/png" data-link=
ed-resource-container-id=3D"524654655" data-linked-resource-container-versi=
on=3D"17" alt=3D"" height=3D"291"></span></p>
<p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manu=
al-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image" draggable=3D"false" width=
=3D"468" src=3D"98ddd9568ab44bd8a1efffdc7f1518d3" data-image-src=3D"/downlo=
ad/attachments/524654655/Screenshot%202026-02-25%20114644.png?version=3D1&a=
mp;modificationDate=3D1772007437599&amp;api=3Dv2" data-unresolved-comment-c=
ount=3D"0" data-linked-resource-id=3D"526254607" data-linked-resource-versi=
on=3D"1" data-linked-resource-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resource-defa=
ult-alias=3D"Screenshot 2026-02-25 114644.png" data-base-url=3D"https://con=
fluence.snapp.ir" data-linked-resource-content-type=3D"image/png" data-link=
ed-resource-container-id=3D"524654655" data-linked-resource-container-versi=
on=3D"17" alt=3D"" height=3D"291"></span></p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-Step2:FeatureEngineering"><strong>Step 2: =
Feature Engineering</strong></h2>
<p>Feature Selection is one of the most critical steps in data science. It =
combines business insight (domain knowledge) with statistical techniques (d=
ata science methods). Below, I explain the rationale behind the selected fe=
atures and how to evaluate their quality. The selection was inspired by the=
 standard <strong>RFM framework (Recency, Frequency, Monetary)</strong>, wh=
ich is key in retail businesses. Since the number of purchases is fixed for=
 all users (4 purchases), the focus is on the other two parameters.&nbsp;In=
 this step, we consolidate the 4 transaction rows of each user into a&nbsp;=
<strong>single feature row</strong> that <strong>summarizes their behavior =
over four purchases</strong>. To better capture user behavior, features are=
 grouped into three main categories:</p>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-1.StatisticalFeatures(Aggregates):">1. Sta=
tistical Features (Aggregates):</h3>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><em>Mean</em> and <em>standard deviation</em> of purchase value and it=
em count.<br><strong>Rationale:</strong> The mean reflects the user=E2=80=
=99s purchasing <strong>power</strong>, while the standard deviation indica=
tes the <strong>consistency </strong>of their behavior.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-2.TemporalFeatures(Recency&amp;Pace):">2. =
Temporal Features (Recency &amp; Pace):</h3>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p>Time intervals between the first and last purchase, and specifically b=
etween the<strong> 3rd and 4th purchase</strong>.<br><strong>Rationale:</st=
rong> Increasing gaps between purchases may signal declining user interest.=
</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-3.TrendFeatures:">3. Trend Features:</h3>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p>Growth rate of purchase value from the first to the fourth transaction=
.<br><strong>Rationale:</strong> Users whose basket value is increasing ove=
r time are <strong>more likely to return</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embed=
ded-manual-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image" draggable=3D"fals=
e" width=3D"350" src=3D"1e69710e500c3c09619655638d8b4d83" data-image-src=3D=
"/download/attachments/524654655/Screenshot%202026-02-23%20194753.png?versi=
on=3D1&amp;modificationDate=3D1771863544419&amp;api=3Dv2" data-unresolved-c=
omment-count=3D"0" data-linked-resource-id=3D"524654827" data-linked-resour=
ce-version=3D"1" data-linked-resource-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resou=
rce-default-alias=3D"Screenshot 2026-02-23 194753.png" data-base-url=3D"htt=
ps://confluence.snapp.ir" data-linked-resource-content-type=3D"image/png" d=
ata-linked-resource-container-id=3D"524654655" data-linked-resource-contain=
er-version=3D"17" alt=3D"" height=3D"330"></span></strong></p>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-Time(Recency&amp;Pace):">Time (Recency &am=
p; Pace):</h3>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p>In churn modeling, timing is the most critical factor.</p></li>
 <li>
  <p><em>last_interval:</em> A large gap between the 3rd and 4th purchase i=
ndicates that the user may be losing interest.</p></li>
 <li>
  <p><em>total_duration:</em> Shows how quickly the user completed their fi=
rst 4 purchases.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-Monetary&amp;Quantity:">Monetary &amp; Qua=
ntity:</h3>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><em>order_value_mean:</em> Reflects the user=E2=80=99s purchasing powe=
r.</p></li>
 <li>
  <p><em>carton_count_std:</em> Captures variability in purchase volume. Us=
ers who consistently buy similar quantities tend to have more predictable=
=E2=80=94and usually more loyal=E2=80=94behavior.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-BasketDiversity:">Basket Diversity:</h3>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><em>line_of_factor:</em> Measures the diversity of items purchased. Us=
ers who buy across more product categories typically become more attached t=
o the platform (<strong>sticky users</strong>).</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-Step3:Modeling&amp;Comparison"><strong>Ste=
p 3: Modeling &amp; Comparison</strong></h2>
<p>At this stage, the goal is to identify the model with the strongest abil=
ity to distinguish between loyal and churned users. To ensure a fair compar=
ison, the following standards were applied:</p>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-AlgorithmSelection:">Algorithm Selection:<=
/h3>
<p>Five different algorithms were evaluated, covering a broad spectrum of m=
odeling approaches:</p>
<p><strong>Logistic Regression</strong><br>
  Used as a <strong>baseline model</strong> to assess linear relationships =
between engineered features and churn probability.</p>
<p><strong>Decision Tree</strong><br>
  Selected to capture simple non-linear relationships while maintaining int=
erpretability in decision-making.</p>
<p><strong>Random Forest</strong><br>
  Chosen due to its ensemble learning capability and high stability on smal=
l datasets through variance reduction (bagging).</p>
<p><strong>XGBoost</strong><br>
  Included as a state-of-the-art boosting algorithm, known for its strong p=
erformance in structured/tabular data problems.</p>
<p><strong>MLP (Neural Network)</strong><br>
  Tested to evaluate whether shallow neural architectures could extract add=
itional non-linear patterns beyond tree-based models.</p>
<p>This diversified selection ensured that conclusions were not biased towa=
rd a single modeling philosophy.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Primary Evaluation Metric (ROC-AUC):</strong><br>
  Due to the imbalanced dataset, <strong>ROC-AUC</strong> was used instead =
of accuracy. This metric better reflects the model=E2=80=99s ability to sep=
arate the two classes.</p>
<p><strong>Scaling:</strong><br>
  Since linear models and neural networks are sensitive to feature scale, a=
ll features were standardized before training.</p>
<p><strong>Stratified K-Fold Cross-Validation:</strong><br>
  The dataset was split into<strong> 5 folds</strong>, and each model was <=
strong>evaluated 5 times</strong>. This approach ensures that the results a=
re <strong>not driven by randomness</strong>=E2=80=94especially important g=
iven the <strong>limited data size</strong>=E2=80=94and preserves the class=
 distribution in each fold.</p>
<p><strong>1.Why Use Cross-Validation?</strong></p>
<p>Normally, we split data into <strong>train and test sets</strong> (e.g.,=
 80/20). However, in this project, we only have <strong>120 labeled samples=
</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Problem with a Single Split:</strong><br>
  If we divide the data just once, the test set contains only 24 users. Ima=
gine if 3 or 4 <strong>outlier users</strong> end up in that small test set=
=E2=80=94model accuracy could fluctuate dramatically, making it unreliable.=
</p>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong><br>
  In <strong>5-Fold Cross-Validation</strong>, the dataset is split into 5 =
equal parts. The model is trained 5 times, each time using <strong>one part=
 as the test set</strong> and the remaining 4 parts as the training set.</p=
>
<p><strong>Result:</strong><br>
  Every user appears <strong>exactly once</strong> in a test set. This prov=
ides a much more <strong>stable and realistic estimate</strong> of model pe=
rformance, independent of which users happen to fall into the test set.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>2.Why 5 Folds? (Why Not 10 or 3?)</strong></p>
<p>Choosing the number of folds (k) is a&nbsp;<strong>trade-off between bia=
s and variance</strong>:</p>
<p><strong>If k=3D10:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p>90% of data is used for training (lower bias).</p></li>
 <li>
  <p>But the test set is very small (only 12 users).</p></li>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Main problem=E2=80=94class imbalance:</strong> We have only 15=
 churned users (Class 0). With 10 folds, each test set would have just 1=E2=
=80=932 churned users. If the model misclassifies even one of them, the acc=
uracy for that fold would drop by 50%! This leads to <strong>high variance<=
/strong> in results.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>If k=3D3:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p>Test sets are larger (40 users), but training sets shrink to 80 users.=
</p></li>
 <li>
  <p>With only 80 samples, the model may <strong>underfit</strong> and fail=
 to capture complex patterns (high bias).</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Why 5 Folds is Optimal:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p>Each test fold has about 24 users, with roughly 3 churned users per fo=
ld. This is <strong>the minimum needed</strong> to reliably compute metrics=
 like Recall or AUC.</p></li>
 <li>
  <p>Meanwhile, 96 users (=E2=89=8880% of the data) remain for training, wh=
ich is sufficient for tree-based models like Random Forest.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>3.WhyStratified K-Fold:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>I used <strong>Stratified K-Fold</strong> to ensure that the <strong>t=
arget class distribution</strong> remains consistent across all training an=
d evaluation folds. Given that we only have 15 churned samples, this techni=
que prevents situations where a test fold contains <strong>no churned users=
</strong>, which would bias the evaluation results.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-InitialHyperParameterTuningStrategy:Manual=
">Initial Hyper Parameter Tuning Strategy: Manual</h3>
<p>In the first phase, models were trained using manually selected hyperpar=
ameters (e.g., <code>max_depth=3D7</code>, <code>class_weight=3D'balanced'<=
/code>).</p>
<p>The purpose of this stage was rapid benchmarking and behavioral explorat=
ion</p>
<p><strong>1. Logistic Regression</strong></p>
<p><strong><code>class_weight=3D'balanced'</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> Our dataset is highly imbalanced (105 loyal user=
s vs. 15 churned users). This parameter tells the model to assign<strong> h=
igher weight and penalty</strong> to mistakes on the minority class (churne=
d users). Without it, the model would learn to predict everyone as =E2=80=
=9Cloyal=E2=80=9D to achieve high apparent accuracy, which is misleading.</=
p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><code>random_state=3D42</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> Ensures that results are exactly the same on eve=
ry run, providing <strong>reproducibility</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>2. Decision Tree</strong></p>
<p><strong><code>max_depth=3D7</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> The tree depth controls its complexity. With onl=
y 120 training samples, an unrestricted tree could memorize every data poin=
t (<strong>overfitting</strong>). A depth of 7 strikes a balance between le=
arning meaningful patterns and avoiding noise.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><code>criterion=3D'entropy'</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> This criterion measures the <strong>purity</stro=
ng> of nodes. Entropy is more sensitive to small probability changes than G=
ini, and in imbalanced datasets, it often produces <strong>sharper decision=
 boundaries</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><code>min_samples_split=3D10</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> A node is only allowed to split if it contains a=
t least 10 samples. This prevents the creation of very small, meaningless b=
ranches.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>3. Random Forest&nbsp;(Winning Model)</strong></p>
<p><strong><code>n_estimators=3D200</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> This is the number of trees in the forest. More =
trees make the model more stable and reduce variance. With our dataset size=
, 200 trees are sufficient for the <strong>=E2=80=9Cwisdom of the crowd=E2=
=80=9D</strong> effect to stabilize predictions.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><code>max_depth=3D7</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> Similar to a single decision tree, this limits t=
he complexity of each individual tree to prevent overfitting.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><code>max_features=3D'sqrt'</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> At each split, only the square root of the total=
 number of features is considered. This ensures that trees are diverse and =
less correlated with each other, which is a key principle of Random Forests=
.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>4. XGBoost&nbsp;</strong></p>
<p><strong><code>scale_pos_weight=3D7</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> This parameter is an advanced form of class weig=
hting. Given the approximate 7:1 ratio (105 loyal vs. 15 churned), it tells=
 the model to give <strong>7 times more importance to the churned class</st=
rong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><code>learning_rate=3D0.05</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> A small learning rate ensures the model learns <=
strong>slowly and steadily</strong>. With limited data, a high learning rat=
e (e.g., 0.3) could make the model fit too quickly to the training data, re=
ducing its ability to generalize.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><code>max_depth=3D3</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> Boosting algorithms rely on <strong>weak learner=
s</strong>. Shallow trees (depth 3) prevent overfitting and keep each step =
simple.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><code>subsample=3D0.8</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> Only 80% of the data is randomly used at each it=
eration. This prevents the model from depending too heavily on specific row=
s and improves robustness.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>5. MLP (Neural Network)</strong></p>
<p><strong><code>hidden_layer_sizes=3D(8, 4)</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> With only 120 training samples, large layers (e.=
g., 100 neurons) would be disastrous. We used a <strong>very small, funnel-=
shaped structure</strong> so the network focuses on capturing only the most=
 general patterns.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><strong><code>alpha=3D0.1</code>:</strong></p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p><strong>Why?</strong> This is the <strong>L2 regularization</strong> p=
arameter. A larger value keeps the network weights small, preventing extrem=
e fluctuations and <strong>overfitting</strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<p><br></p>
<p>In all models, my primary focus was on <strong>controlling overfitting</=
strong>, given the very small training dataset (120 users). Additionally, b=
y using <strong>class weighting parameters</strong>, I forced the models to=
 carefully monitor the behavioral patterns of churned users (Class 0) despi=
te the limited number of samples.</p>
<p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manu=
al-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image" draggable=3D"false" width=
=3D"350" src=3D"cf537f092d87c91ad41a4474984b67b8" data-image-src=3D"/downlo=
ad/attachments/524654655/Screenshot%202026-02-24%20120700.png?version=3D1&a=
mp;modificationDate=3D1771923059542&amp;api=3Dv2" data-unresolved-comment-c=
ount=3D"0" data-linked-resource-id=3D"524655530" data-linked-resource-versi=
on=3D"1" data-linked-resource-type=3D"attachment" data-linked-resource-defa=
ult-alias=3D"Screenshot 2026-02-24 120700.png" data-base-url=3D"https://con=
fluence.snapp.ir" data-linked-resource-content-type=3D"image/png" data-link=
ed-resource-container-id=3D"524654655" data-linked-resource-container-versi=
on=3D"17" alt=3D"" height=3D"169"></span></p>
<p>Due to the <strong>limited dataset size</strong>, bagging-based models (=
like Random Forest) demonstrated <strong>greater stability</strong> compare=
d to boosting-based models.</p>
<p><br></p>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-FinalHyperParameterTuningStrategy:GridSear=
chCV">Final Hyper Parameter Tuning Strategy: GridSearchCV</h3>
<p>After identifying <strong>Random Forest</strong> and <strong>XGBoost</st=
rong> as top-performing candidates, the workflow shifted from heuristic tun=
ing to systematic optimization.</p>
<p><strong>Why GridSearchCV?</strong><br>
  To ensure that no optimal hyperparameter combinations (e.g., number of es=
timators, learning rate, tree depth) were overlooked.</p>
<p>To prevent biased evaluation, <strong>Stratified 5-Fold Cross-Validation=
</strong> was embedded within GridSearch. This ensured:</p>
<ul>
 <li>
  <p>Stable performance estimation across folds</p></li>
 <li>
  <p>Preservation of class distribution in every split</p></li>
 <li>
  <p>Reduced variance in AUC measurements</p></li>
 <li>
  <p>Protection against random favorable splits</p></li>
</ul>
<p>This approach increased confidence that performance improvements were ge=
nuine and not artifacts of data partitioning.</p>
<h3 id=3D"ChurnPredictionProject-FinalResultsandModelSelection">Final Resul=
ts and Model Selection</h3>
<p>After tuning, <strong>Random Forest</strong> and <strong>XGBoost</strong=
> achieved comparable and strong performance (AUC =E2=89=88 0.66).</p>
<p><strong>Random Forest</strong><br>
  Demonstrated high robustness due to its <strong>bagging mechanism</strong=
>, making it resistant to noise and variance in small datasets.</p>
<p><strong>XGBoost</strong><br>
  Leveraged <strong>regularization </strong>and <strong>sequential error co=
rrection</strong>, showing strong capability in identifying minority-class =
(churn) patterns.</p>
<p>The outputs of both models were analyzed separately when predicting the =
80 unlabeled users, providing complementary perspectives on churn risk.</p>
<p><span class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manu=
al-size"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image" draggable=3D"false" width=
=3D"400" src=3D"c9c8284087b3471886c9045b8e048be6" data-image-src=3D"/downlo=
